# Security Review: `app.js`

I've reviewed the Express application. It's very small, but even a 23-line file can contain several meaningful security issues — and, more importantly, it's missing a lot of defense-in-depth that should be baked in *before* the app grows. Here's the assessment.

---

## Summary

| Severity | Count |
|---|---|
| High | 2 |
| Medium | 5 |
| Low | 3 |
| Informational | 2 |

The app itself doesn't contain classic injection sinks (no SQL, no `child_process`, no template rendering, no user input reflected), so traditional injection risk is **low**. The real issues are **missing authentication, missing security middleware, PII exposure, and insecure defaults**.

---

## Findings

### 🔴 HIGH — H1: Unauthenticated PII Disclosure (`A01: Broken Access Control`, `A04: Insecure Design`)

```js
app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json([
    { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' },
    { id: 2, name: 'Bob', email: 'bob@example.com' },
  ]);
});
```

Names + emails are PII. The endpoint has **no authentication, no authorization, no rate limit**, so anyone who can reach the port can enumerate every user. Under GDPR/UK-DPA this is a reportable data exposure in production.

**Fix — require auth and scope the response:**

```js
const jwt = require('jsonwebtoken');

function requireAuth(req, res, next) {
  const header = req.get('authorization') || '';
  const [scheme, token] = header.split(' ');
  if (scheme !== 'Bearer' || !token) {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'unauthorized' });
  }
  try {
    req.user = jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_PUBLIC_KEY, { algorithms: ['RS256'] });
    next();
  } catch {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'invalid_token' });
  }
}

function requireScope(scope) {
  return (req, res, next) => {
    if (!req.user?.scopes?.includes(scope)) {
      return res.status(403).json({ error: 'forbidden' });
    }
    next();
  };
}

app.get('/users', requireAuth, requireScope('users:read'), (req, res) => {
  // ...return only data the caller is entitled to see
});
```

Also consider pagination and field minimization — don't return `email` unless the caller's scope includes it.

---

### 🔴 HIGH — H2: No Security Headers (`A05: Security Misconfiguration`)

The app never installs `helmet`, so responses are missing `Strict-Transport-Security`, `X-Content-Type-Options`, `Content-Security-Policy`, `Referrer-Policy`, etc. Express also advertises itself via `X-Powered-By: Express`, which aids fingerprinting.

**Fix:**

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');

app.disable('x-powered-by');
app.use(helmet({
  hsts: { maxAge: 63072000, includeSubDomains: true, preload: true },
  contentSecurityPolicy: { useDefaults: true, directives: { 'default-src': ["'none'"] } }, // API, no HTML
  referrerPolicy: { policy: 'no-referrer' },
}));
```

---

### 🟠 MEDIUM — M1: No Rate Limiting / DoS Protection (`A04: Insecure Design`)

Any endpoint — especially `/users` — can be hit without limit. An attacker can enumerate, scrape, or cause denial of service.

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');

app.use(rateLimit({
  windowMs: 60_000,
  max: 60,                       // tune per endpoint
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
}));
```

